  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Record and Inscription for the Blue Stone Pagoda of Kaecheonsa Temple
  author: Lee Gyeong-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Prince of Guangling, a man of the royal house, dwelt in high station yet harbored thoughts that transcended the dusty world, serene and untouched. Among his companions beyond the mundane realm was a certain eminent monk who discovered an ancient temple called Kaecheon in the southern lands of Fengshui County. As he set about its renewal, the Prince became its patron, contributing greatly to the work. The master's senior disciple Hyungyu, witnessing this, sighed and spoke: "My teacher has built thus grandly, yet I who dwell in his presence have accomplished not one worthy deed—surely this brings me shame." Thereupon he erected what is called in Sanskrit a stupa, fashioned entirely of blue stone, spiraling upward in thirteen tiers. Upon its completion, he reported to the Prince, saying: "Though monks like myself return to earth when we die, what good are we if we pass our days in idle ease, accomplishing nothing of merit, only to vanish like morning dew? How then shall we repay the nation's grace? It is this thought that moved me to raise this modest stone pagoda. Though now completed, I await one versed in letters to inscribe it, that it may endure eternal." Hearing these words, the Prince admired the monk's steadfast and incorruptible heart, and sent word to Lee Chun-kyung of Long-xi, entrusting him with the inscription. Though I claim no mastery of letters, I cannot in conscience obscure another's virtue, nor can I refuse the Prince's request. Thus I have ventured to inscribe these words, in the first year of His Majesty's reign.

    The Inscription:

    In Twin Grove fades the Great One,
    Our Buddha passed to cessation—
    Yet if we say he ceased to be,
    All things alike are emptiness.
    Though the stone tower stands complete,
    What dwells within its form?
    Cessation is no cessation,
    But the realm where afflictions end.
    In countless transformed bodies
    He appears where'er we look.

    So too this pagoda—
    It is a dwelling of the Buddha.
    Where does Buddha come from?
    What then is this stone?
    See the tower, forget the tower:
    Only thus the treasure shines.
    Through this pagoda's presence,
    We behold all Buddhas true.
  footnotes:
    - 'Stupa (Sanskrit: चतुष्पद, stūpa): a sacred mound or tower in Buddhist architecture, typically containing relics and serving as an object of veneration.'
    - 'Twin Grove (Shala grove): the place where Shakyamuni Buddha entered parinirvana, his final passing.'
    - The inscription employs Buddhist philosophical paradox—the negation of appearance to reveal ultimate reality—a technique central to Chan/Zen Buddhist thought.
